english:
  title: Postscript to the Collected Works of Master Maeheon
  author: An Ji
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In my youth, I frequented the halls of the National Academy, where Master Maeheon served as its chief director. There he championed the study of moral philosophy and taught with untiring devotion. Scholars from all quarters, hearing of his renown, gathered like clouds, day after day. It was then that I studied the Book of Changes beneath his desk.

    One day, the Master expounded upon the numbers of the odd and even, illuminating his teaching with this example: "This is easy to understand. When a person takes a meal, he first grasps the spoon, then takes up the chopsticks. The spoon is single, the chopsticks are paired—such is the natural order. Yet people rarely perceive it." Though I am dull of wit, I trembled at these words, as if suddenly glimpsing some profound truth. I thought to myself: the craftsman surely did not consciously embed the principles of yin and yang in these daily implements and their sequence. Yet there exists within heaven and earth a natural mathematics that even the humblest artisan cannot escape. From that time forward, through observing the particulars of things and pondering their principles, I came to understand much. I have held these teachings fast in my heart, vowing to preserve them throughout my life. Truly, the Master was my teacher.

    In the year ylchuk, the Master's second son, Magistrate Ki of the Bureau of War, came and showed me his father's surviving manuscripts. He said: "My father's poems and writings were numerous, yet many have been lost. My elder brother, the Right Censor, was able to preserve only some fragments before his untimely passing. This remains my deepest sorrow." Since receiving these works, I have returned to them again and again, unable to set them down. Now Magistrate Ki, having been appointed to Geumsan County, writes to me: "My father's manuscripts have long awaited publication. Our provincial governor, Minister Kim, a student of my father, shares this wish. Censor Jeong of Hadong has already written a preface—will you compose the postscript?"

    I believe the Master, though born into a distinguished family, achieved mastery of the scholarly arts. His literary gifts and moral character rivaled those of his elder brother, Master Yangchon, and both were celebrated in their time. His poetry and prose are like refined gold and lustrous jade—solid and upright, gentle and elegant, crystalline and intricate. The longer one reads them, the deeper their flavor becomes. Only one who has penetrated learning and fathomed the Way could achieve such perfection. My only regret is that so little of his work survives. It is only fitting that these be carved into woodblocks and transmitted to posterity. Moreover, when his second son passed the examination, I, though unworthy, participated as an examiner. My connection to the Master's household runs deep. I cannot refuse, moved as I am by his generous guidance in former days. Thus do I gladly compose these words, both to express my enduring admiration and to honor his memory.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Baanseu (泮水): The sacred waters bordering the National Academy (Seonggyungwan), used metaphorically for the Academy itself.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Master Maeheon: A renowned Neo-Confucian scholar and educator of the Joseon period.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The odd and even (寄耦): A fundamental concept in Change philosophy relating to singular and paired principles.'
  - key: ''
    value: The spoon and chopsticks metaphor demonstrates how natural principles (yin-yang, odd-even) manifest in everyday objects and practices.
  - key: ''
    value: 'Yangchon: The Master''s elder brother, also a celebrated scholar and official.'
